r will be higher if it makes it easier for humans or for computers to locate your data set, e.g. if it ends up in an index or has a unique resolvable identifier."},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"0feac7e6-add4-4723-abae-be5ce7864c63","abbreviation":"A","eventType":"AddMetricEvent","title":"Accessibility","uuid":"c19feec6-2ab2-4757-893a-c11c47f352b8","parentUuid":"6f6241d9-136c-4770-9d58-8a3f39607052","description":"The Accessibility metric describes how well the access to the database is described and how easy it is to implement. The score associated with an answer will be higher if it makes it easier for humans and computers to get to the data. This is determined by e.g. the protocol for accessing the data or for authenticating users, and also by the guaranteed longevity of the repository. Note that this is different from the Openness metric!"},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"a42bded3-a085-45f8-b384-32b4a77c8385","abbreviation":"I","eventType":"AddMetricEvent","title":"Interoperability","uuid":"412854a9-ee08-4630-8e9a-71978c8290b3","parentUuid":"6f6241d9-136c-4770-9d58-8a3f39607052","description":"The Interoperability metric describes how well the data interoperates with other data. The score associated with an answer will be higher if it makes it easier for humans and computers to couple the data with other data and ''understand'' relationships. This is influenced by the use of standard ontologies for different fields and proper descriptions of the relations. It is also influenced by proper standard metadata that is agreed by the community."},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"0bafe0c2-a8f2-4c74-80c8-dbf3a5b8e9b7","abbreviation":"R","eventType":"AddMetricEvent","title":"Reusability","uuid":"b0bf9ac7-cd4c-4e77-9d56-2363e558bc8e","parentUuid":"6f6241d9-136c-4770-9d58-8a3f39607052","description":"The Reusability metric describes how well the data is suitable for reuse in other context. The score associated with an answer will be higher if it makes it easier for humans and computers to reuse the data. This is influenced largely by proper description of how the data was obtained, and also by the conditions that are put on the reuse (license and, for personally identifying information, consent)."},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"8845fe2b-79df-4138-baea-3a035bf5e249","abbreviation":"G","eventType":"AddMetricEvent","title":"Good DMP Practice","uuid":"c99e578d-f4cc-4a36-94cc-1451901f11fe","parentUuid":"6f6241d9-136c-4770-9d58-8a3f39607052","description":"The Good DMP Practice metric describes how appreciated a process is among Data Stewards. A score associated with an answer will be high if a practice would be considered preferable over alternatives, generally a good idea."},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"cc02c5a0-9754-4432-a7e0-ce0f3cf7a0a0","abbreviation":"O","eventType":"AddMetricEvent","title":"Openness","uuid":"04d738dd-3b71-4433-afd6-65b105fa71cd","parentUuid":"6f6241d9-136c-4770-9d58-8a3f39607052","description":"The Openness metric describes how Open the data are available. Note that this is different from the Accessibility metric. A score associated with an answer will be high if the data will be as open as possible, and low if voluntary restrictions apply to access and re-use."},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","text":"Before you decide to embark on any new study, it is nowadays good practice to consider all options to keep the data generation part of your study as limited as possible. It is not because we can generate massive amounts of data that we always need to do so. Creating data with public money is bringing with it the responsibility to treat those data well and (if potentially useful) make them available for re-use by others.","entityUuid":"82fd0cce-2b41-423f-92ad-636d0872045c","eventType":"AddChapterEvent","title":"Design of experiment","uuid":"ad05e39e-78a5-4856-a803-1f3f1c49f189","parentUuid":"6f6241d9-136c-4770-9d58-8a3f39607052"},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","text":"Are there any data sets available in the world that are relevant to your planned research?","entityUuid":"efc80cc8-8318-4f8c-acb7-dc1c60e491c1","questionType":"OptionsQuestion","eventType":"AddQuestionEvent","title":"Is there any pre-existing data?","requiredPhaseUuid":"1796fa3c-9f53-475f-89ff-c66a0453c42e","tagUuids":[],"uuid":"09239ce6-8fa6-46a0-9204-9601b9c62dcf","parentUuid":"82fd0cce-2b41-423f-92ad-636d0872045c"},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"e48cb16a-0efc-4ff9-b673-7190176c8b94","eventType":"AddReferenceEvent","uuid":"010ec99c-23e3-4e75-857f-444c73c20d04","parentUuid":"efc80cc8-8318-4f8c-acb7-dc1c60e491c1","shortUuid":"atq","referenceType":"ResourcePageReference"},{"advice":"You know that this is very unlikely? This question is not only about data sets that are similar to what you want to determine yourself, but also reference data or data that should be mined from the existing literature. Further, it is very likely that you will refer to related data, e.g. other databases where you usually \"quickly look something up\", but that could maybe be properly integrated, especially if you need to do such lookups multiple times.","annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"72cdbc99-2707-4817-ac40-435a03e5e837","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"No","uuid":"73ad390a-62e0-4326-8cc5-9d97ea87b7d7","parentUuid":"efc80cc8-8318-4f8c-acb7-dc1c60e491c1","metricMeasures":[]},{"advice":null,"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"2663b978-5125-4224-9930-0a50dbe895c9","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"Yes","uuid":"eb672e04-a139-4c33-b42c-19c94fdd28ef","parentUuid":"efc80cc8-8318-4f8c-acb7-dc1c60e491c1","metricMeasures":[]},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","text":"Will you be referring to any earlier measured data, reference data, or data that should be mined from existing literature? Your own data as well as data from others?","entityUuid":"59efe0c4-fc18-4082-a656-6d0c1db45899","questionType":"OptionsQuestion","eventType":"AddQuestionEvent","title":"Will you be using any pre-existing data (including other people''s data)?","requiredPhaseUuid":"1796fa3c-9f53-475f-89ff-c66a0453c42e","tagUuids":[],"uuid":"95f712bd-7030-47a6-8c57-8ff4d7687d96","parentUuid":"2663b978-5125-4224-9930-0a50dbe895c9"},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"e51c1e39-92cf-4d80-89eb-76b8dc4e790c","eventType":"AddReferenceEvent","uuid":"efd35b89-49a4-45ad-b91e-ef460b2ed5c7","parentUuid":"59efe0c4-fc18-4082-a656-6d0c1db45899","shortUuid":"ezi","referenceType":"ResourcePageReference"},{"advice":"Did you research all the data that exists? You may not be aware of all existing data that could be available. Although using and/or integrating existing data sets may pose a challenge, it will normally be cheaper than collecting everything yourself. Even if you decide not to use an existing data set, it is better to do this as a conscious decision.","annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"18a860e6-4f77-459e-bfeb-24949924ac44","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"No","uuid":"79a267e8-291e-405d-882c-23e483ad704c","parentUuid":"59efe0c4-fc18-4082-a656-6d0c1db45899","metricMeasures":[]},{"advice":null,"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"dac677d4-99f9-4af8-935a-4a1c9c7cdbdf","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"Yes","uuid":"10c296b9-99ba-46aa-bb21-e1767a8f9fbe","parentUuid":"59efe0c4-fc18-4082-a656-6d0c1db45899","metricMeasures":[]},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","text":"Much of todays data is used in comparison with reference data. A genome for instance is compared with a reference genome to identify genomic variants. If you use reference data, there are several other issues that you should consider. What are the reference data sets that you will use?","entityUuid":"fcc51962-08df-4f4c-85ad-6bb932107010","questionType":"ListQuestion","eventType":"AddQuestionEvent","title":"What reference data will you use?","requiredPhaseUuid":"1796fa3c-9f53-475f-89ff-c66a0453c42e","tagUuids":[],"uuid":"69ce2f34-6706-4355-af69-f89ac1df9b0a","parentUuid":"dac677d4-99f9-4af8-935a-4a1c9c7cdbdf"},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"916487d3-cd03-4248-994a-6ff850680189","eventType":"AddReferenceEvent","uuid":"17c2d8df-3fb3-4369-a9a5-230443a106c3","parentUuid":"fcc51962-08df-4f4c-85ad-6bb932107010","shortUuid":"quc","referenceType":"ResourcePageReference"},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"37fcb07e-a791-40ef-934b-33dedece5b0c","eventType":"AddReferenceEvent","targetUuid":"588ad032-56ba-4d52-b29c-6a5b56aa6569","uuid":"9e817c0a-142c-449b-a677-d540a8bc867c","parentUuid":"fcc51962-08df-4f4c-85ad-6bb932107010","referenceType":"CrossReference","description":"Creating reference data"},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","text":"Do you know where the reference data is available, what the conditions for use are, and how to reference it?","entityUuid":"9ac2713c-6aa1-4884-a93f-2ac727d00567","questionType":"OptionsQuestion","eventType":"AddQuestionEvent","title":"Do you know where and how is it available?","requiredPhaseUuid":"1796fa3c-9f53-475f-89ff-c66a0453c42e","tagUuids":[],"uuid":"c61ffcb3-90e6-4afb-8bdf-b5486a263623","parentUuid":"fcc51962-08df-4f4c-85ad-6bb932107010"},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"f5bc753d-0f58-46b0-a4d7-79db4d61914e","eventType":"AddReferenceEvent","uuid":"8384fcfb-a24c-4443-a5f3-ecf5c6e5c381","parentUuid":"9ac2713c-6aa1-4884-a93f-2ac727d00567","shortUuid":"ckt","referenceType":"ResourcePageReference"},{"advice":"Figure this out quickly!","annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"08bed2b3-fe76-48e5-a884-7f2658f90845","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"No","uuid":"6d1b1d94-cfa6-4526-9d40-0619351e326d","parentUuid":"9ac2713c-6aa1-4884-a93f-2ac727d00567","metricMeasures":[]},{"advice":null,"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"14a7b8cd-7edb-4dab-937b-36b42726fe6e","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"Yes","uuid":"1a6a9fb2-5fba-48de-95f5-27944b1f449b","parentUuid":"9ac2713c-6aa1-4884-a93f-2ac727d00567","metricMeasures":[]},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","text":"Do you know the data format of the reference data? Is this suitable for your work? Does it need to be converted?","entityUuid":"7b8c75c0-8d5c-4fde-9898-ded8b91f7f1f","questionType":"OptionsQuestion","eventType":"AddQuestionEvent","title":"Do you know in what format the reference data is available?","requiredPhaseUuid":"1796fa3c-9f53-475f-89ff-c66a0453c42e","tagUuids":[],"uuid":"ca137923-fe90-4c54-9277-348f01647bd5","parentUuid":"fcc51962-08df-4f4c-85ad-6bb932107010"},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"b0bf7cd9-6527-441f-bdab-835b6948dd87","eventType":"AddReferenceEvent","uuid":"6c95d7c2-6ef5-42f3-b024-e1dc4697a464","parentUuid":"7b8c75c0-8d5c-4fde-9898-ded8b91f7f1f","shortUuid":"jxb","referenceType":"ResourcePageReference"},{"advice":null,"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"2c2a9b84-b140-4e17-8026-56d5372064d0","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"I can directly use it","uuid":"fdf80f2c-1d9e-4cfa-9d0f-d5d0f16e1b27","parentUuid":"7b8c75c0-8d5c-4fde-9898-ded8b91f7f1f","metricMeasures":[]},{"advice":null,"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"9de86d7b-9c60-47d6-8cb1-bfca13d6f619","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"I need to convert it before using","uuid":"c5cd1f42-c252-49de-8cfe-70bfa5d76444","parentUuid":"7b8c75c0-8d5c-4fde-9898-ded8b91f7f1f","metricMeasures":[]},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","text":"Many reference data sets evolve over time. If the reference data set changes, this may affect your results. If different versions of a reference data set exist, you need to establish your \"version policy\".","entityUuid":"10b6548c-21cd-44c8-a8de-47415e7b012e","questionType":"OptionsQuestion","eventType":"AddQuestionEvent","title":"Is the reference data resource versioned?","requiredPhaseUuid":"1796fa3c-9f53-475f-89ff-c66a0453c42e","tagUuids":[],"uuid":"a2014c69-540e-4d82-a9db-debb1f502bf0","parentUuid":"fcc51962-08df-4f4c-85ad-6bb932107010"},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"998c065c-bb3b-44ff-937e-5e2e7fa4d56f","eventType":"AddReferenceEvent","uuid":"93a3ab9b-2a40-4c91-b8f8-ce49bfacfd1b","parentUuid":"10b6548c-21cd-44c8-a8de-47415e7b012e","shortUuid":"rgy","referenceType":"ResourcePageReference"},{"advice":null,"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"32c9e457-8289-4825-9334-83ff87adeb3f","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"No","uuid":"486bbbe5-f2a0-4b3c-a346-8e2f1658b6bc","parentUuid":"10b6548c-21cd-44c8-a8de-47415e7b012e","metricMeasures":[]},{"advice":null,"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","entityUuid":"842007ce-0951-4655-8acc-b0f582e82ea1","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"Yes","uuid":"4aef4062-1311-42c7-bbf6-d5fe4195bf72","parentUuid":"10b6548c-21cd-44c8-a8de-47415e7b012e","metricMeasures":[]},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2018-10-01T00:00:00Z","text":"If there are different versions available, you have to decide with all project partners together which version you will be using. Probably you will go for the latest release as of the date of the start of your research project. However, if you have other data from older projects that need to be merged, you may need to consider using the same release you used for a previous project.","entityUuid":"f00a28fb-ac77-4110-b285-c73c8bc62630","questionType":"ValueQuestion","eventType":"AddQuestionEvent","title":"Which version will you use?","requiredPhaseUuid":"1796fa3c-9f53-475f-89ff-c66a0453c42e","tagUuids":[]