etect early when data files are damaged or mixed up. It can also be helpful to keep the list under version control so that all changes are well documented.","changed":true},"entityUuid":"e0759fdc-7ce9-4020-816d-73119f634c7e","questionType":"OptionsQuestion","eventType":"EditQuestionEvent","title":{"changed":false},"requiredPhaseUuid":{"changed":false},"tagUuids":{"changed":false},"uuid":"b517eadc-6468-4615-b88e-da9e19bd31e6","expertUuids":{"changed":false},"parentUuid":"8608d3df-7d7f-4893-8f80-e5297167b213","answerUuids":{"changed":false},"referenceUuids":{"changed":false}},{"annotations":{"changed":false},"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","text":{"value":"The FAIR principles ask for the use of FAIR ontologies. It is better when using RDF to make use as much as possible of concepts that are in established and well-maintained ontologies on the internet.","changed":true},"entityUuid":"3196c225-2842-4766-9768-381fd6ee1e05","questionType":"OptionsQuestion","eventType":"EditQuestionEvent","title":{"value":"Are all the URIs in the RDF resolving to common ontologies?","changed":true},"requiredPhaseUuid":{"changed":false},"tagUuids":{"changed":false},"uuid":"2fe095cd-126b-4809-a174-193db44ecb40","expertUuids":{"changed":false},"parentUuid":"3525f6f9-4c0b-4560-a572-c9fe2e0a0d94","answerUuids":{"changed":false},"referenceUuids":{"changed":false}},{"advice":{"changed":false},"annotations":{"changed":false},"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","entityUuid":"945aae79-4eed-4115-ac19-d295158a19f6","eventType":"EditAnswerEvent","followUpUuids":{"changed":false},"label":{"value":"No, some concepts are internal to the project and we refer to our own ontologies","changed":true},"uuid":"7b18724d-ba60-4634-939b-20e20bbbf5b5","parentUuid":"3196c225-2842-4766-9768-381fd6ee1e05","metricMeasures":{"value":[{"weight":1,"measure":0.5,"metricUuid":"a42bded3-a085-45f8-b384-32b4a77c8385"}],"changed":true}},{"advice":null,"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","entityUuid":"30a6e365-dbf6-4567-96c3-b7301d0fd0ca","eventType":"AddAnswerEvent","label":"No, we made our own ontologies for our work; concepts are not mapped to common ontologies","uuid":"b44d7de1-8fd3-4ea6-953f-608900212fb5","parentUuid":"3196c225-2842-4766-9768-381fd6ee1e05","metricMeasures":[]},{"annotations":{"changed":false},"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","text":{"changed":false},"entityUuid":"3196c225-2842-4766-9768-381fd6ee1e05","questionType":"OptionsQuestion","eventType":"EditQuestionEvent","title":{"changed":false},"requiredPhaseUuid":{"changed":false},"tagUuids":{"changed":false},"uuid":"48e222ac-7444-4875-bcf6-ca219c35cf7a","expertUuids":{"changed":false},"parentUuid":"3525f6f9-4c0b-4560-a572-c9fe2e0a0d94","answerUuids":{"value":["30a6e365-dbf6-4567-96c3-b7301d0fd0ca","945aae79-4eed-4115-ac19-d295158a19f6","88f9fb7b-12a9-481a-9239-cbf43206056e"],"changed":true},"referenceUuids":{"changed":false}},{"advice":{"changed":false},"annotations":{"changed":false},"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","entityUuid":"30a6e365-dbf6-4567-96c3-b7301d0fd0ca","eventType":"EditAnswerEvent","followUpUuids":{"changed":false},"label":{"changed":false},"uuid":"43ebeeaa-0d7f-40a7-a21b-77b34dddfe99","parentUuid":"3196c225-2842-4766-9768-381fd6ee1e05","metricMeasures":{"value":[{"weight":1,"measure":0,"metricUuid":"a42bded3-a085-45f8-b384-32b4a77c8385"}],"changed":true}},{"advice":{"changed":false},"annotations":{"changed":false},"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","entityUuid":"88f9fb7b-12a9-481a-9239-cbf43206056e","eventType":"EditAnswerEvent","followUpUuids":{"changed":false},"label":{"value":"Yes, (almost) all our concepts are either from common ontologies, or mapped to common ontologies","changed":true},"uuid":"53d3ed97-9a6a-4a1d-8b54-4808cfd4c11d","parentUuid":"3196c225-2842-4766-9768-381fd6ee1e05","metricMeasures":{"changed":false}},{"advice":{"changed":false},"annotations":{"changed":false},"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","entityUuid":"945aae79-4eed-4115-ac19-d295158a19f6","eventType":"EditAnswerEvent","followUpUuids":{"changed":false},"label":{"value":"No, we exclusively refer to our own ontologies for some classes of objects","changed":true},"uuid":"a621b776-779d-4ae8-86ee-6e6ae3ea92ab","parentUuid":"3196c225-2842-4766-9768-381fd6ee1e05","metricMeasures":{"changed":false}},{"annotations":{"changed":false},"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","text":{"value":"Although there is no world-wide rule for the application of copyright on data sets (copyright only applies to things that require a so-called \"creative step\"), it is wise to check for an explicit permission to use a data set and not to assume that data can be used freely just because you can access it. \nNote that copyright laws explicitly *forbid* the use of a copyrighted work, *except* if you get permission. Such a permission is called a \"licence\". So: if you can not find a licence, you have to assume you can not use the data.","changed":true},"entityUuid":"69999c2c-2710-480e-b8ac-8a8fc6f582e5","questionType":"OptionsQuestion","eventType":"EditQuestionEvent","title":{"changed":false},"requiredPhaseUuid":{"changed":false},"tagUuids":{"changed":false},"uuid":"67f6ece4-b9ef-41ae-8b28-04076bbba2e6","expertUuids":{"changed":false},"parentUuid":"be872000-cb98-442f-999c-ca3ef58dcfe8","answerUuids":{"changed":false},"referenceUuids":{"changed":false}},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Copyright","entityUuid":"81667fbe-dd42-4b28-a956-66a31f064e38","eventType":"AddReferenceEvent","label":"Wikipedia on Copyright","uuid":"94024693-0041-4c3d-9064-5561b8808321","parentUuid":"69999c2c-2710-480e-b8ac-8a8fc6f582e5","referenceType":"URLReference"},{"annotations":{"changed":false},"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","text":{"value":"Although there is no world-wide rule for the application of copyright on data sets (copyright only applies to things that require a so-called \"creative step\"), it is wise to check for an explicit permission to use a data set and not to assume that data can be used freely just because you can access it. \nNote that copyright laws explicitly *forbid* the use of a copyrighted work, *except* if you get permission. Such a permission is called a \"licence\". So: if you can not find a licence, you have to assume you can not use the data.","changed":true},"entityUuid":"aee03da5-b399-4274-8db4-fac82c6210d3","questionType":"OptionsQuestion","eventType":"EditQuestionEvent","title":{"changed":false},"requiredPhaseUuid":{"changed":false},"tagUuids":{"changed":false},"uuid":"65435dde-ccf5-43fc-9e21-055f1f9d0789","expertUuids":{"changed":false},"parentUuid":"fcc51962-08df-4f4c-85ad-6bb932107010","answerUuids":{"changed":false},"referenceUuids":{"changed":false}},{"annotations":[],"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Copyright","entityUuid":"720e0101-8b99-438b-a6e5-8ae9386c7b0c","eventType":"AddReferenceEvent","label":"Wikipedia on Copyright","uuid":"191bdd65-918b-43cd-84c0-5da174a7f1a4","parentUuid":"aee03da5-b399-4274-8db4-fac82c6210d3","referenceType":"URLReference"},{"annotations":{"changed":false},"createdAt":"2020-11-11T10:49:19.845Z","text":{"value":"Much of todays data is used in comparison with reference data. You may be comparing your own data with a \"standard set\" which is maintained as a collection by someone else. Or you could be determining differences to a standard (for example in bioinformatics, a genome is often compared with a reference genome to identify genomic variants). If you use reference data, there are several specific issues that you should consider. What are the reference data sets that you will use?","changed":true},"entityUuid":"fcc51962-08df-4f4c-85ad-6bb932107010","questionType":"ListQuestion","eventType":"EditQuestionEvent","itemTemplateQuestionUuids":{"changed":false},"title":{"changed":false},"requiredPhaseUuid":{"changed":false},"tagUuids":{"changed":false},"uuid":"b8b143fc-ba6b-44de-81